\begin_layout Abstract
The measure of agreement called 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 was invented to handle the paradox of kappa, but does it rest on solid
 foundations? Gwet's motivation for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 match is based on guessing models, and we argue the recently developed
 knowledge coefficient far better, with the details narrowing it down to
 the Brennan–Prediger coefficient.
 We argue that the weighted variant of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

, called 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{2}$
\end_inset

, is inappropriately defined, and provide an alternative.
 In addition, Gwet's estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is based on an approximation, and will be asymptotically biased.
 But we provide an exact formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

, whose plugin estimator is consistent for Gwet's original definition.
 Finally, we will generalize the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{AC}_{2}$
\end_inset

 to different classes of guessing models than the rather restrictive class
 considered by Gwet.
\end_layout

