\begin_layout Standard
The percent agreement is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}=117/125=0.9440$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, the Fleiss-type chance agreement is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{f}=0.9456$
\end_inset

.
 Here the raters agree less than would be expected due to chance alone,
 hence the resulting Fleiss kappa is negative.
 The resulting Fleiss' kappa is 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.9440-0.9456)/(1-0.9456)=-0.0288$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some researchers believe this to paradoxical.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Feinstein1990-zb"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest solution to the paradox of kappa, when dealing with nomial
 data, is the Brennan–Prediger coefficient, also known under many different
 names, defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa_{BP}=\frac{p_{a}-C^{-1}}{1-C^{-1}}.\label{eq:Brennan-Prediger coefficient}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The main problem with the Brennan–Prediger lies in its motivation: Why are
 we justified in defining chance agreement as 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{-1}$
\end_inset

? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can write chance-corrected measures of agreement on the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{x-y}{1-y}=x-(1-x)\frac{y}{1-y}=x-(1-x)\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}y^{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Let's say that a chance-corrected measure of agreement 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is paradox-free if 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa>0$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}>C^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability of chance agreement can be defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{X\sim F_{1}\times F_{2}}1[X_{1}=X_{2}]=\sum_{i=1}^{C}p_{1}(i)p_{2}(i)=p_{1}^{T}p_{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x>(1-x)\frac{y}{1-y},\quad x>C^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset

This ensures that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa>0$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}>C^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 We want 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}>C^{-1}$
\end_inset

 since 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
W
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $y\leq C^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 However, if 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a probability of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{T}p$
\end_inset

, then this is minimized in 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 This provides an argument for 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1-y)x>(1-x)y
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 introduces 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

as a solution to the paradox of kappa.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Guessing models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The joint distribution of the 
\emph on
guessing model
\emph default
 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x\mid s,x^{\star})=\prod_{r=1}^{R}\left[s_{r}1[x_{r}=x^{\star}]+(1-s_{r})q_{r}(x_{r})\right].\label{eq:full guessing model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $x_{r}$
\end_inset

 is the rating given by the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

th judge on an item.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $s=\{s_{1},s_{2},\ldots,s_{r}\}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\emph on
skill-difficulty parameters
\emph default
, the probabilities that the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

th judge knows the correct classification of an item.
 The skill-difficulty parameters can be deterministic or random.
 For instance, they can be sampled from a Beta distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is the true classification the item, an unknown latent variable.
 These are assumed to be independent of the skill-difficulty parameters
 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 The distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x^{\star})$
\end_inset

, the 
\emph on
true rating distribution
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $q_{r}(x)$
\end_inset

 are the 
\emph on
guessing distributions
\emph default
, the distributions the ratings are drawn from when the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

th judge does not know the true classification of the item.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have introduced the guessing model in order to define the notion of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

agreement due to knowledge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in a precise way.
 To gain an intuition about what we're getting at, first consider the case
 of two judges with potentially different, but deterministic, skill-difficulty
 parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The probability that two judges agree on the classification of an item
 because they both know its classification is the product of their skill
 parameters, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=s_{1}s_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

agree on classification of an item because they both know its classification
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is cumbersome to read, we will call it 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

knowledgeable agreement
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

agree knowledgeably
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from now.
 Extending this notion to 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 judges, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{r_{1}>r_{2}}s_{r_{1}}s_{r_{2}}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that a randomly selected pair of judges will agree knowledge
ably on a pair of ratings.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another simple case happens when there are 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 judges with random skill-difficulty parameters that do not wary across
 judges when the item is fixed, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}=S_{2}=\cdots=S_{R}$
\end_inset

, where we use capital letters to emphasize that the 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{r}$
\end_inset

 are random.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $E(S_{r}^{2})$
\end_inset

 is the probability of knowledgeable agreement.
 Finally, in the general guessing model, we find that the probability of
 knowledgeable agreement among two judges is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nu=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{r_{1}>r_{2}}E[S_{r_{1}}S_{r_{2}}].\label{eq:knowledgable agreement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

