\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Perreault–Leigh model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Perreault1989-mg"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 discussed an explicit model for the rating process.
 In their terminology, they used 
\begin_inset Formula $R=2$
\end_inset

 raters, a equal and deterministic skill-difficulty parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 for both raters, uniform guessing distributions, and an arbitrary true
 distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x)$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting univariate model is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x)=\sigma t(x)+(1-\sigma)C^{-1}.\label{eq:Perreault--Leigh model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

From this model they derived that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\sigma}=\sqrt{(p_{a}-1/C)/(1-1/C)}$
\end_inset

, the square root of the Brennan–Prediger coefficient.
 It follows that the knowledge coefficient equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{BP}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Perreault1989-mg"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 reported reported the root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{BP}$
\end_inset

, but we won't follow their lead in this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Perreault–Leigh model is strongly related to model used by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in his motivation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

.
 The only modification is that he allows for different skill-difficulty
 parameters for both raters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Knowledge coefficient theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main result concerning knowledge coefficients is Theorem 2 of Moss (2023).
 Under suitable assumptions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 equals classical agreement coefficients or variants of them.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 equals the Brennan–Prediger coefficient if all guessing distributions are
 uniform, and the weighted Fleiss' kappa or Cohen's kappa if all guessing
 distributions are marginal.
 Theorem 2 is summarized in Table 
