\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most important consequence of Theorem 2 is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\kappa_{BP}$
\end_inset

 when every rater's guessing distribution is uniform.
 Be aware that is true for both random and deterministic skill-difficulty
 parameters and for all true rating distributions.
 
\emph on
The only
\emph default
 crucial assumption is the uniformity of the guessing distribution.
 There are several arguments for this assumption.
 For instance Gwet (2014) states.
 A reasonable counter-argument would be that raters are reasonably aware
 of the true distribution, and are likely to guess according to it.
 However, then the 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Guessing models and the paradox of kappa
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we have seen, the knowledge coefficient for the model with all guessing
 distributions equal to the marginal distribution equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{F}=\kappa_{C}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that the paradox of kappa also holds for guessing models.
 Let's see what happens.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 be the true distribution of ratings, and assume the guessing distributions
 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{r}$
\end_inset

 are equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x\mid s,x^{\star})=\left[s_{1}1[x_{1}=x^{\star}]+(1-s_{1})t(x_{1})\right]\left[s_{2}1[x_{2}=x^{\star}]+(1-s_{2})t(x_{2})\right].
\]

\end_inset

Taking expectations with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\star}$
\end_inset

, we find
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x_{1},x_{2}\mid s)=s_{1}s_{2}t(x_{1})1[x_{1}=x_{2}]+(1-s_{1}s_{2})t(x_{1})t(x_{2})
\]

\end_inset

Now consider the true distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x_{1})=0.97$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x_{2})=0.03$
\end_inset

.
 We can write out the distribution as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{1}s_{2}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0.97 & 0\\
0 & 0.03
\end{array}\right]+(1-s_{1}s_{2})\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0.9409 & 0.0291\\
0.0291 & 0.0009
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=0$
\end_inset

 even when the raters disagree only 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx5.82\%$
\end_inset

 of the time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the raters guess uniformly at random from 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 categories, however, then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p(x_{1},x_{2}\mid s) & = & s_{1}s_{2}t(x_{1})1[x_{1}=x_{2}]+(1-s_{1})(1-s_{2})C^{-2}\\
 &  & +(s_{2}-\nu)C^{-1}t(x_{2})+(s_{1}-\nu)C^{-1}t(x_{1}).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x_{1})=0.97$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x_{2})=0.03$
\end_inset

 once more and let 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}=s_{2}$
\end_inset

, placing us in the context of the Perrault–Leigh model.
 We can write the distribution as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s^{2}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0.97 & 0\\
0 & 0.03
\end{array}\right]+(1-s)^{2}\frac{1}{4}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1\\
1 & 1
\end{array}\right]+(1-s)s\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0.97 & 0.015\\
0.015 & 0
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0$
\end_inset

, the distribution places weight 
\begin_inset Formula $1/4$
\end_inset

 on each observation pair, a far cry from the weight of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.0291$
\end_inset

 in the Fleiss model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Defining the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the beginning of Section 4 of his paper 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Computing inter-rater reliability and its variance in the presence of high
 agreement
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describes the context of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

, in the context of two raters 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 rating subjects into two categories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Before I introduce an improved alternative inter-rater reliability coefficient,
 it is necessary to develop a clear picture of the goal one normally attempts
 to achieve by correcting inter-rater reliability for chance agreement.
 My premises are the following: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Chance agreement occurs when at least one rater rates an individual randomly.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Only an unknown portion of the observed ratings is subject to randomness.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Quote
I will consider that a rater 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 classifies an individual into one of two categories either randomly, when
 he or she does not know where it belongs, or with certainty, when he or
 she is certain about its ‘true’ membership.
 Rater 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 performs a random rating not all the time, but with a probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{A}$
\end_inset

 is the propensity for rater 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to perform a random rating.
 The participants not classified randomly are supposed to have been classified
 into the correct category.
 [...]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Point (2) and the paragraph below it places us squarely in the domain of
 guessing models.
 Point (1) provides a definition of chance agreement, which we denote by
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{g}$
\end_inset

 (for Gwet type chance agreement).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is knowledgable agreement, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{a}=\nu+p_{g}.\label{eq:gwet chance agreement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using this notion of chance agreement, but without reference 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, Gwet defines the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

 (eq.
 17) as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma=\frac{p_{a}-p_{g}}{1-p_{g}}.\label{eq:ac1-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Observe that, according to the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}=\nu+p_{g}$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma=\frac{\nu}{1-p_{a}+\nu}.\label{eq:ac1-formulation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the remainder of the paper, he makes the assumption that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

[...] random rating would normally lead to the classification of an individual
 into either category with the same probability 1/2.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (p.
 37).
 In our terminology, the guessing distributions are uniform.
 From Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:coefficients"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we see that, provided all guessing distributions are uniform, we have that
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\nu_{BP}$
\end_inset

, the Brennan–Prediger coefficient.
 It immediately follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\frac{\nu_{BP}}{1-p_{a}+\nu_{BP}}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, using the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{BP}$
\end_inset

, it is easy to remove the dependence on either 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{BP}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Suppose the guessing distributions are uniform for all raters.
 Then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

 equals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma=\frac{C\nu_{BP}}{(C-1)+\nu_{BP}}=\frac{Cp_{a}-1}{C+p_{a}-2}.\label{eq:ac1-multirater-perrault-leigh}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Using that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}=\nu_{BP}+C^{-1}(1-\nu_{BP})$
\end_inset

 together with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ac1-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\nu_{BP}$
\end_inset

 when all guessing distributions are uniform, we find that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\gamma=\frac{\nu_{BP}}{1-p_{a}+\nu_{BP}} & = & \frac{\nu_{BP}}{1-\nu_{BP}-C^{-1}(1-\nu_{BP})+\nu_{BP}}\\
 & = & \frac{C\nu_{BP}}{(C-1)+\nu_{BP}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The second equality follows similarily.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
(i) This generalizes eq.
 24 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2008-nf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to the case of more than two categories, multiple raters, and random skill-diff
iculty parameters.
 (ii) Estimating 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 only requires the estimation of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

, which is quite simple, along with an application of the delta rule.
 See section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "sec:Inference-and-estimation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Be aware that 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Chapter 4"
key "Gwet2014-iu"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 redefined the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma^{\star}=\frac{p_{a}-p_{g}^{\star}}{1-p_{g}^{\star}},\quad p_{g}^{\star}=\frac{1}{C-1}\sum_{c=1}^{C}p(c)(1-p(c))=\frac{1-p_{f}}{C-1},\label{eq:AC1 approximation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{f}$
\end_inset

 is the Fleiss-type probability of chance agreement.
 Originally, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "eq. 22"
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 presented 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\star}$
\end_inset

 as an approximation to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Gwet correct"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, not the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient itself.
 In this paper we will understand 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Gwet correct"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 as the population 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient, 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 the approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 We do not see any reason for using this approximation, even though the
 population bias is quite small when 
\begin_inset Formula $C=2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

 as defined in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ac1-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can is defined in any guessing model.
 Moreover, the knowledge coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 can be estimated by classical agreement coefficients under the various
 assumptions of Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:coefficients"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 If none of these assumptions can be assumed to hold, it is also possible
 to attempt maximum likelihood estimation, as done by, e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Aickin1990-nj"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2014-iu"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proposed a weighted variant of the redefined 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

, christened the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{2}$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{p_{wa}-p_{wg}^{\star}}{1-p_{wg}^{\star}},\quad\textrm{where }p_{wg}^{\star}=\frac{1-p_{f}}{C-1}\frac{\sum_{x,y}w(x,y)}{C}.
\]

\end_inset

The motivation behind 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{g}^{\star}(w)$
\end_inset

 is hard to follow, possibly because it is based directly on the approximation
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{g}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 instead of the correct 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{g}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We believe the most natural weighted generalization of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{w}=\frac{\nu}{1-p_{wa}+\nu}.
\]

\end_inset

To see why, recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}=\nu+p_{g}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{wa}=\nu+p_{wg}$
\end_inset

 for any weighting function with 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x,x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 This should be reasonably clear, as the knowledge coefficient is invariant
 with respect to weights, considering that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 only counts 100% agreement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The case against the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our case against the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

 can be split into three.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If you wish to use chance-corrected measures of agreement, it is inappropriate
 to use 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{g}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Agreement lie in their generality.
 They are defined for any distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, and do not depend on the validity of a hypothetical guessing model for
 their interpretation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $p_{g}$
\end_inset

 does not correspond to the agreement of a natural probability distribution.
 In this sense it is unprincipled.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Guessing models are quite unrealistic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{AC}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is even weirder.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, let us discuss why we care about chance-corrected measures of agreement
 in the first place.
 For illustration, consider the quadratically weighted Cohen's kappa.
 It can be defined in terms of the probability of disagreement and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

probability of chance disagreement
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the following way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa=1-\frac{p_{d}}{p_{cd}}=1-\frac{E_{X\sim F}([X_{1}-X_{2}]^{2})}{E_{X\sim F_{1}\times F_{2}}([X_{1}-X_{2}]^{2})},\label{eq:quadratic kappa}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

) is the rating of the first (second) judge on the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th item.
 The numerator 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{X\sim F}([X_{1}-X_{2}]^{2})$
\end_inset

 answers the question 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

How close is the rating of judge 1 to the rating of judge 2 when they rate
 the same item?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Likewise, the denominator answers the question 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

How close is the rating of judge 1 to the rating of judge 2 when they rate
 distinct items?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The numerator serves as a reasonable baseline for evaluating the predictive
 power of judge 2s rating.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main attraction of chance-corrected measures of a
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Estimation and inference 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Inference-and-estimation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the generalized 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ac1-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\frac{\nu}{1-p_{a}+\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 To estimate this, you may choose your assumptions from Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:coefficients"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, estimate the associated 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\nu}$
\end_inset

, estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{a}$
\end_inset

, then employ the plugin estimator
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\gamma}=\frac{\hat{\nu}}{1-\hat{p_{a}}+\hat{\nu}}.\label{eq:ac1_estimator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the guessing distributions are uniform, the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is particularily simple 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ac1-multirater-perrault-leigh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{BP}=\frac{Cp_{a}-1}{C+p_{a}-2}.
\]

\end_inset

The derivative with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(C-1)^{2}/(C+p_{a}-2)^{2}$
\end_inset

, hence an application of the delta method implies that the asymptotic variance
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{BP}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{\gamma_{BP}}^{2}=\sigma_{A}^{2}\frac{(C-1)^{2}}{(C+p_{a}-2)^{2}},\label{eq:AC1 plugin var}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{A}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the asymptotic variance of the chance agreement, which is easily estimable
 using the theory of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 statistics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The asymptotic variance of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

 under different conditions is somewhat harder to state and derive.
 We must employ the multivariate delta method to do inference on 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\gamma}$
\end_inset

.
 Ignoring the Cohen–Fleiss kappa and Cohen–Brennan–Prediger coefficients
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ignoring these are justified, as the Cohen–Brennan–Prediger was found to
 be highly non-robust and the Cohen–Fleiss coefficient very similar to Cohen's
 kappa and Fleiss' kappa by Moss (2023).
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we can write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{c}=\frac{\nu_{c}}{1-p_{a}+\nu_{c}}=\frac{p_{a}-p_{c}}{(p_{a}-2)p_{c}+1},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{c}$
\end_inset

 is either 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{CF}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset

.
 The gradient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{c}$
\end_inset

 equals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
