\begin_layout Subsection
Comparison to Gwet's method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume the guessing distributions are uniform.
 We will compare the coverage of normal theory confidence interval derived
 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AC1 plugin var"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, using the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

-distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom and to the confidence interval described by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The true distribution of ratings is fixed at 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.1,0.05,0.65,0.1,0.2)$
\end_inset

.
 In Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "tab:coverage ac-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we see that the methods have comparable coverage when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is small, but with the coverage of Gwet's method becoming steadily worse
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 increases.
 This is hardly surprising considering the population value of Gwet's approximat
ion 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\star}$
\end_inset

 does not equal the true 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

.
 However, the biases are quite small, between 
\begin_inset Formula $0.01$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.03$
\end_inset

 in these simulations.
 Biases of this magntiude evidently matter only when the sample size is
 large.
 
\end_layout

